#: ../../plans.rst:42 ../../plans.rst:145
msgid "Aspiration"
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:44
msgid ""
"The aspiration or ambition is *what you are aiming towards*. It's the "
"answer to the question: \"What do you *want*?\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:46
msgid ""
"You are *here*, and you desire to be *there*; your aspiration lies in a "
"certain direction. It is the value that gives your whole plan meaning; "
"it's something you believe in because it's worth reaching for."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:48
msgid ""
"*Ambitions don't need to be particularly realistic to have value.* They "
"should have at least a little wildness in them, because a safe and "
"comfortable ambition isn't going to inspire you."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:50
msgid ""
"A plan without aspiration is without meaning, value or direction - it's "
"empty."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:54 ../../plans.rst:84 ../../plans.rst:111
msgid "Examples"
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:56
msgid "I want to start and develop a successful software business."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:57
msgid "I want to achieve the highest results in my studies."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:58
msgid "I want to support my family through my work."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:62
msgid "Not succeeding in your aspirations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:64
msgid ""
"We don't always reach what we aim for - especially when we aim for "
"ambitious things (it would be easy to achieve all your ambitions by "
"aiming only for unambitious things). If the direction is a good one, "
"you'll find valuable things along the way, even if you don't reach the "
"destination."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:66
msgid ""
"In a way, it doesn't matter too much. If you strive towards an ambitious "
"goal, you're likely to get *somewhere* worthwhile, even if it were not "
"precisely what you had expected or hoped for."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:70 ../../plans.rst:151
msgid "Objectives"
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:72
msgid ""
"The objectives, naturally, are *objective measures*. They are the answer "
"to the question: \"What shall you *achieve*?\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:74
msgid ""
"Objectives are the milestones you reach on the journey towards your "
"ambition, the things you make happen and the outcomes you bring about "
"through your efforts. You - and others - will be able to see that you are"
" making progress as you achieve the outcomes you set out."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:76
msgid ""
"Objectives need to be realistic, even if they are ambitious. It makes no "
"sense to set yourself an objective you can't meet."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:78
msgid ""
"A meaningful objective usually includes a *time component* whether "
"implicit or explicit: how long it will take to achieve it."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:80
msgid ""
"A plan without measurable objectives is a fantasy, detached from reality "
"or rigour."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:86
msgid "By the end of the year, I aim to be invoicing at least USD 1000 per month."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:87
msgid ""
"I aim to submit two pull requests fixing bugs in <open source project> "
"each month."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:88
msgid "I aim to complete all my coursework one week before the final deadline."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:89
msgid "I aim to achieve the <such-and-such> certification before June."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:93
msgid "Not attaining your objectives"
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:95
msgid ""
"You should attain *most* of your objectives - they need to be fairly "
"reasonable. If you can easily achieve them all, that's a bit suspicious -"
" they were probably a bit unambitious. If you never achieve any, either "
"they were completely unrealistic, or perhaps something else is going "
"wrong."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:99 ../../plans.rst:156
msgid "Commitments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:101
msgid ""
"Commitments in a plan are *the things you promise to do*. They are the "
"answer to the question: \"What will you *do*?\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:103
msgid ""
"In a plan, you commit to particular actions. Every action is an effort "
"towards your ambition, that helps bring about an objective."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:105
msgid ""
"You can only commit to something you can achieve through an act of will, "
"something you can choose to do. You can't *choose* to do well in an "
"examination, but you can choose to spend each evening studying instead of"
" going out with your friends."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:107
msgid ""
"Real commitments tend to include time commitments - *when* you are going "
"to do what you promised."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:113
msgid ""
"I will set aside 1 hour a day for four weeks to study for the exam (until"
" 31st May)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:114
msgid "I will join the undergraduate Python study group."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:115
msgid "1st-2nd June: I will attend the weekend seminar."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:116
msgid "I will attend the local developers' meetup (Wednesday evenings)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:117
msgid "I will apply to join the open-source code volunteers programme."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:118
msgid "I will work through all exercises in the <such-and-such> book."
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:122
msgid "Not keeping your commitments"
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:124
msgid ""
"Not completing the activities you said you would is a failure to respect "
"your commitments. It is literally failing to do your work. (Occasionally,"
" you can be forgiven - for example if you realise that in good faith, you"
" promised more than you could give - but that should be a rare "
"occurrence.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:130
msgid "Writing out your plan"
msgstr ""

#: ../../plans.rst:132
msgid ""
"A plan will not be successful unless it is written down. That puts it "
"outside you - if it stays inside your head, you can tell yourself "
"anything about it, and you will successfully fool yourself."
msgstr ""

